Mitchell,
You just hit on exactly what I&#39;ve been working on setting up my NEAT
application to search for. 
My approach is to use the neat package to evolve a network that is good
at learning, which I think is in essence what you saw in the lemur
behaviour.
Currently, the strength in evolutionary algorithms is to us &#39;species
learning&#39; to create an indevidual that is good at some task that the
programmer describes with a fitness function. The evolved network can
have dynamic behaviour, but it is generally incapable of interesting
time dependant behaviour. 
I believe that history dependance in the transfer function of each
neuron, in addition to recurrent connections, should shed some insight
into powerfull short term memory. 
There do exist neuron structures that have strong long term memory, I
don&#39;t remember now what they were called, but perhapes in the future we
will understand long term and short term memory structures well enought
to integrate them into the current evolutionary framework, and we can
then write fitness functions that promote learning as the desired
behaviour.
I hope this is what you were thinking about, cause I get excited talking
about it...
chad

